00:51:20.337 --> 00:51:28.337
To make the dashboard, we will change the format from HTML to dashboard.

00:51:28.337 --> 00:51:34.337
Once you do that, I recommend stripping out all the text in your document and even all the headers in the beginning,

00:51:34.337 --> 00:51:36.337
leaving just the code cells.

00:51:36.337 --> 00:51:40.337
Each code cell will become its own card in the dashboard.

00:51:40.337 --> 00:51:45.337
That means it will just have a self-contained box, keeping everything in that code cell together.

00:51:45.337 --> 00:51:48.337
And those cards by default will be laid out one on top of another.

00:51:48.337 --> 00:51:53.337
So each card sort of makes its own row in the dashboard.

00:51:53.337 --> 00:51:56.337
And that's a fine layout, but not particularly sophisticated.

00:51:56.337 --> 00:52:03.337
You can control this layout, and the way you can control it with Cordo is by putting headers back into your document.

00:52:03.337 --> 00:52:10.337
The text of the headers will not appear anywhere, but the fact that there is a header there will change the layout.

00:52:10.337 --> 00:52:16.337
Each second-level header you add to your document will start a new row in the dashboard,

00:52:16.337 --> 00:52:23.337
and everything will be arranged in that row until you tell it to make a new row at this point.

00:52:23.337 --> 00:52:30.337
So here if I add these two second-level headers in these two places, those four cards would now be arranged like this into two rows.

00:52:30.337 --> 00:52:33.337
I'm skipping over first-level headers. You can put those in there too.

00:52:33.337 --> 00:52:40.337
Those make different tabs in your dashboard. It's a website thing, but I don't have enough content to worry about tabs.

00:52:40.337 --> 00:52:47.337
If you want to break it up even further, you might want to take one of those rows and put columns in it.

00:52:47.337 --> 00:52:49.337
You can do that with a third-level header.

00:52:50.337 --> 00:52:57.337
So within the row defined by the second-level header, I can now make two columns defined by these third-level headers,

00:52:57.337 --> 00:53:03.337
and everything in a column will be arranged going down in the column until I start a new column.

00:53:03.337 --> 00:53:05.337
That's how I get this layout.

00:53:05.337 --> 00:53:13.337
Now, by experimenting with those two things, you can create half of the dashboard layouts that you imagine.

00:53:14.337 --> 00:53:22.337
The other half will be layouts that begin by splitting your dashboard by columns, not by splitting it by rows.

00:53:22.337 --> 00:53:34.337
You can get to those by adding this second value up here, orientation columns.

00:53:34.337 --> 00:53:38.337
It just flips everything. So now the cards are laid out one column at a time.

00:53:38.337 --> 00:53:42.337
Now second-level headers start a new column.

00:53:42.337 --> 00:53:46.337
And now third-level headers start a row within the column.

00:53:46.337 --> 00:53:50.337
So it just exactly flips what happened before.

00:53:50.337 --> 00:53:57.337
Between those two things, you now can spend enough time with the fiddly details, make any sort of arrangement you want.

00:53:57.337 --> 00:54:04.337
The last bit of power that's missing is right now core is going to split everything in equal proportions,

00:54:04.337 --> 00:54:08.337
but sometimes a good layout isn't split equally.

00:54:08.337 --> 00:54:16.337
If you want to change the width or the height of one of these elements, you can do that when you set the header.

00:54:16.337 --> 00:54:20.337
And you can either change the height or the width with this syntax.

00:54:20.337 --> 00:54:22.337
It's borrowed from CSS.

00:54:22.337 --> 00:54:26.337
Use braces, no quotation marks, and no spaces.

00:54:26.337 --> 00:54:32.337
You can set the height to some percentage of the thing it's occupying.

00:54:32.337 --> 00:54:40.337
So this would make that row only 30% of the total column height that it's in.

