01:17:44.761 --> 01:17:46.562
Let's talk about Shiny.

01:17:46.562 --> 01:17:49.602
Shiny is a wonderful package for R.

01:17:49.602 --> 01:17:51.442
You've probably heard of it before.

01:17:51.442 --> 01:17:53.081
Maybe you've used it before.

01:17:53.081 --> 01:17:55.442
If not, I'll tell you what it's all about.

01:17:55.442 --> 01:17:57.602
In the past, I'd spend half a day to a whole day

01:17:57.602 --> 01:18:00.282
teaching you how to build your first Shiny app.

01:18:00.322 --> 01:18:03.241
In the age of AI, that's no longer necessary.

01:18:03.241 --> 01:18:06.162
Shiny is also available for both R and Python

01:18:06.162 --> 01:18:07.961
for those who said use Python.

01:18:07.961 --> 01:18:09.562
But today, we're just gonna use R.

01:18:09.562 --> 01:18:13.241
So like Cordo, Shiny has a wonderfully well-documented

01:18:13.241 --> 01:18:16.041
webpage at shiny.posit.co.

01:18:16.041 --> 01:18:18.081
Anything you wanna dig into deeper here

01:18:18.081 --> 01:18:20.921
or things we don't cover about Shiny today,

01:18:20.921 --> 01:18:23.801
you can learn here at shiny.posit.co.

01:18:23.801 --> 01:18:27.402
And what we'll focus on today

01:18:27.402 --> 01:18:29.241
is understanding the concept of Shiny

01:18:29.241 --> 01:18:30.801
and being able to interpret and check up

01:18:30.801 --> 01:18:33.602
on what AI writes when we tell it to write Shiny.

01:18:33.602 --> 01:18:35.201
So the way you think of a Shiny app

01:18:35.201 --> 01:18:37.002
is it is a webpage,

01:18:37.002 --> 01:18:38.722
a webpage that you're gonna build

01:18:38.722 --> 01:18:41.842
only by writing R code or Python code.

01:18:41.842 --> 01:18:45.041
And that webpage will have two classes of things.

01:18:45.041 --> 01:18:47.162
It'll have what I'm gonna call inputs.

01:18:47.162 --> 01:18:50.842
And these are widgets your visitor can manipulate

01:18:50.842 --> 01:18:54.402
with their mouse to provide values to the app.

01:18:54.402 --> 01:18:56.081
Those are things like dropdown menus,

01:18:56.081 --> 01:18:58.882
sliders, calendar date pickers,

01:18:58.961 --> 01:19:01.442
check boxes, the things you've done on the web

01:19:01.442 --> 01:19:04.562
with your mouse, you could do them in Shiny.

01:19:04.562 --> 01:19:07.241
The second class of things are outputs.

01:19:07.241 --> 01:19:09.641
These are things that you can build with R

01:19:09.641 --> 01:19:11.602
and they will appear for the user.

01:19:11.602 --> 01:19:14.961
The idea is the outputs will use the inputs

01:19:14.961 --> 01:19:18.641
that the user provide to give that user a custom experience.

01:19:19.682 --> 01:19:21.481
And we're gonna make that make sense.

01:19:21.481 --> 01:19:24.761
It comes together in actually a pretty elegant way, I think.

01:19:25.602 --> 01:19:29.682
So if the user changed the dropdown menu to stomach cancer,

01:19:29.682 --> 01:19:33.162
it would show the hotspots for stomach cancer in the map.

01:19:33.162 --> 01:19:35.761
But if they change the dropdown menu to an other site,

01:19:35.761 --> 01:19:38.122
that's just like a catch all other types of cancer,

01:19:38.122 --> 01:19:40.641
the map would update to show that data.

01:19:40.641 --> 01:19:42.162
Same map, same place of the app,

01:19:42.162 --> 01:19:43.282
but it's just changing every time

01:19:43.282 --> 01:19:44.761
the user changes their input.

01:19:47.241 --> 01:19:48.521
How do we do that?

01:19:48.521 --> 01:19:51.081
Well, we're going to do it by starting with this code.

01:19:51.081 --> 01:19:53.122
I like to tell people to think of this code

01:19:53.122 --> 01:19:56.641
as a boilerplate or a template for making a Shiny app.

01:19:56.641 --> 01:19:58.562
Every Shiny app you write will start with something

01:19:58.562 --> 01:20:01.882
that looks either exactly like this or very similar to this.

01:20:01.882 --> 01:20:06.402
And I've made it available to you in the app.r file.

01:20:06.402 --> 01:20:08.602
Let's go visit the app.r file and run it

01:20:08.602 --> 01:20:10.722
and see our first Shiny app.

01:20:11.641 --> 01:20:14.521
So if you come to Positron,

01:20:14.521 --> 01:20:16.521
click on the file explorer up here

01:20:17.402 --> 01:20:21.682
and then find app.r and open it.

01:20:22.442 --> 01:20:25.641
You can start closing the other files if you like.

01:20:25.641 --> 01:20:27.641
This is the same code that was on the slide.

01:20:27.641 --> 01:20:30.722
And I consider this to be like the minimal Shiny app.

01:20:30.722 --> 01:20:32.402
When you have a Shiny app open,

01:20:32.402 --> 01:20:35.041
you can run it and preview it in Positron

01:20:35.041 --> 01:20:38.041
by clicking the play button at the top of the file.

01:20:38.041 --> 01:20:41.041
So press that play button and let's see what it does.

01:20:42.282 --> 01:20:44.361
All right, that's what it does.

01:20:44.361 --> 01:20:46.801
It makes a blank Shiny app.

01:20:46.801 --> 01:20:48.122
But notice the one thing it doesn't make,

01:20:48.122 --> 01:20:49.562
it doesn't make an error message.

01:20:49.562 --> 01:20:52.442
This works, this is a viable Shiny app.

01:20:52.442 --> 01:20:56.122
This is what it looks like as a sidebar with nothing in it,

01:20:56.122 --> 01:20:57.801
as a main panel with nothing in it.

01:20:57.801 --> 01:21:00.282
It's waiting for us to add things to it.

01:21:00.282 --> 01:21:01.961
But one thing I wanna draw your attention to,

01:21:01.961 --> 01:21:05.521
there's a red square here, that is a stop button

01:21:05.521 --> 01:21:09.722
because there's now a R process on our server

01:21:09.722 --> 01:21:12.442
or our computer watching this app,

01:21:12.442 --> 01:21:14.801
waiting for the user to change an input

01:21:14.801 --> 01:21:19.041
so the computer can then change the outputs for the user.

01:21:19.041 --> 01:21:20.921
And every Shiny app is built like this.

01:21:20.921 --> 01:21:22.762
There is a computer watching the app,

01:21:22.762 --> 01:21:26.481
ready to serve the user by updating the outputs.

01:21:26.481 --> 01:21:27.682
We call that the server.

01:21:27.682 --> 01:21:30.401
And oftentimes it is a literal web server,

01:21:30.401 --> 01:21:33.682
but when you do it locally, it's your own computer.

01:21:33.682 --> 01:21:35.962
What I found is working with Shiny apps,

01:21:35.962 --> 01:21:37.921
sometimes you do this and you forget that's running

01:21:37.921 --> 01:21:39.682
and you try to run some code and it doesn't run

01:21:39.682 --> 01:21:41.361
because where you try to run it,

01:21:41.361 --> 01:21:42.882
it's busy looking at the Shiny app.

01:21:42.882 --> 01:21:45.002
So it's good practice to always stop this

01:21:45.002 --> 01:21:46.841
after you've previewed the app.

01:21:46.841 --> 01:21:50.202
And then you know everything's ready to do new stuff.

01:21:52.202 --> 01:21:54.401
So you know how to make a blank Shiny app,

01:21:54.401 --> 01:21:56.442
but that's nothing to write home about.

01:21:56.442 --> 01:21:58.762
Let's, we just did that together.

01:21:58.762 --> 01:22:00.882
Let's dissect this and sort of see

01:22:00.882 --> 01:22:03.322
