The last test is just to see if it's interactive

01:27:45.962 --> 01:27:48.122
and it passes.

01:27:48.122 --> 01:27:50.962
All right, so I now have a Shiny app

01:27:50.962 --> 01:27:51.921
that is interactive

01:27:51.921 --> 01:27:54.002
and I can look at the different types of cancer

01:27:54.002 --> 01:27:55.721
one type at a time

01:27:55.721 --> 01:27:58.122
going through this Shiny app.

01:27:58.122 --> 01:27:59.241
So that's pretty cool.

01:27:59.241 --> 01:28:00.442
Let's just take a little peek

01:28:00.442 --> 01:28:01.882
to see how that's wired up

01:28:01.882 --> 01:28:05.241
so you could understand what the AI did

01:28:05.241 --> 01:28:06.481
and if it did a good job.

01:28:07.562 --> 01:28:10.002
There is a solution in 03app.r

01:28:10.002 --> 01:28:12.002
that's where I'm going to draw from

01:28:12.002 --> 01:28:13.721
for the next few slides.

01:28:13.721 --> 01:28:14.562
But to be honest,

01:28:14.562 --> 01:28:17.122
I have no idea what code my AI wrote

01:28:17.122 --> 01:28:18.202
or your AI wrote.

01:28:18.202 --> 01:28:20.002
It is different every time

01:28:20.002 --> 01:28:22.241
but not probably too different.

01:28:22.241 --> 01:28:24.361
So let's start with the UI side of things.

01:28:26.361 --> 01:28:27.762
It put an input in there.

01:28:27.762 --> 01:28:29.601
How does that happen?

01:28:29.601 --> 01:28:32.082
Well, you can put inputs in the UI

01:28:32.082 --> 01:28:33.601
by using a set of functions

01:28:33.601 --> 01:28:34.921
that all begin with something

01:28:34.921 --> 01:28:36.682
followed by input

01:28:36.682 --> 01:28:38.481
provided by Shiny.

01:28:38.481 --> 01:28:40.522
And for each of these functions,

01:28:40.522 --> 01:28:42.161
we're going to pass it the name

01:28:42.161 --> 01:28:44.202
to save a value app.

01:28:44.202 --> 01:28:45.161
Pay attention to that.

01:28:45.161 --> 01:28:47.002
We'll look for it in the code.

01:28:47.002 --> 01:28:48.122
This is a group of functions

01:28:48.122 --> 01:28:49.122
provided by Shiny

01:28:49.122 --> 01:28:51.041
for adding different types of input.

01:28:51.041 --> 01:28:52.562
And you can see they each added,

01:28:52.562 --> 01:28:55.202
you know, a different way of interacting with the app.

01:28:55.202 --> 01:28:56.882
We're going to use select input.

01:28:56.882 --> 01:28:58.762
That's the dropdown menu.

01:28:58.762 --> 01:29:00.361
And then you might find other R packages

01:29:00.361 --> 01:29:02.841
that add additional input functions you can use.

01:29:04.241 --> 01:29:05.801
Each input function

01:29:05.801 --> 01:29:07.762
follows the same basic syntax

01:29:07.762 --> 01:29:08.921
until it gets to arguments

01:29:08.921 --> 01:29:11.442
that are specific to that sort of input.

01:29:11.442 --> 01:29:12.762
But the most important thing

01:29:12.762 --> 01:29:14.841
will always be the first argument

01:29:14.841 --> 01:29:15.921
because that's the name

01:29:15.921 --> 01:29:18.082
that's going to save the user value under.

01:29:18.082 --> 01:29:19.801
You get to choose that name.

01:29:19.801 --> 01:29:21.762
You'll have to look it up later.

01:29:21.762 --> 01:29:22.882
So here I chose site.

01:29:22.882 --> 01:29:25.442
So when that dropdown menu is set to stomach,

01:29:25.442 --> 01:29:29.041
the value of site in something called input

01:29:29.041 --> 01:29:30.442
will be stomach.

01:29:30.442 --> 01:29:32.562
Shiny will collect all the inputs,

01:29:32.562 --> 01:29:33.682
as many as you want,

01:29:33.682 --> 01:29:34.721
you can add to the app.

01:29:34.721 --> 01:29:35.801
We'll put all their values

01:29:35.801 --> 01:29:37.882
in the same list named input.

01:29:37.882 --> 01:29:41.281
So here input site is how I look at that value.

01:29:41.281 --> 01:29:43.322
If I change the dropdown,

01:29:43.322 --> 01:29:46.322
the value of input site will change as well.

01:29:46.322 --> 01:29:47.161
All right.

01:29:49.322 --> 01:29:50.601
We don't have annotation working.

01:29:50.601 --> 01:29:53.041
So look at this for a second

01:29:53.041 --> 01:29:54.242
and see if you could spot

01:29:54.242 --> 01:29:57.362
where the select input function appears.

01:29:58.641 --> 01:30:00.242
I'll show you, it's right there.

01:30:00.242 --> 01:30:01.682
And what I want you to pay attention to

01:30:01.682 --> 01:30:06.041
is it's inside of the sidebar function in our template.

01:30:06.041 --> 01:30:07.761
For this UI stuff,

01:30:07.761 --> 01:30:09.242
it's really simple.

01:30:09.242 --> 01:30:10.482
Where you put the function

01:30:10.482 --> 01:30:12.842
that calls the input or the output

01:30:12.842 --> 01:30:14.442
determines where that input or output

01:30:14.442 --> 01:30:15.842
will live in the app.

01:30:15.842 --> 01:30:16.761
If you put the function

01:30:16.761 --> 01:30:19.322
inside the sidebar portion of the template,

01:30:19.322 --> 01:30:20.842
it will live in the sidebar.

01:30:20.842 --> 01:30:23.641
If you put it outside of the sidebar portion,

01:30:23.641 --> 01:30:25.281
that'd be that function sidebar there.

01:30:25.281 --> 01:30:27.761
It will live outside of the sidebar.

01:30:27.761 --> 01:30:29.121
So our dropdown menu in this case

01:30:29.121 --> 01:30:30.521
will be in the sidebar

01:30:30.521 --> 01:30:32.921
and it's collecting a value called site.

01:30:32.921 --> 01:30:33.962
All right.

01:30:33.962 --> 01:30:36.641
So the next thing that we know in the UI is outputs.

01:30:36.641 --> 01:30:38.202
And it's almost the same thing,

01:30:38.202 --> 01:30:40.242
just wash, rinse and repeat.

01:30:40.242 --> 01:30:41.761
But this time we're using a set of functions

01:30:41.761 --> 01:30:43.521
that are called output functions.

01:30:43.521 --> 01:30:45.322
They also go in the UI.

01:30:45.322 --> 01:30:46.161
In this case,

01:30:46.161 --> 01:30:47.761
we'll probably put them outside the sidebar functions

01:30:47.761 --> 01:30:49.521
so they're not in the sidebar.

01:30:49.521 --> 01:30:53.082
And they also take the name of an object.

01:30:53.082 --> 01:30:55.682
This case will be an object we define somewhere else,

01:30:55.682 --> 01:30:57.442
but that's how they're gonna know what object

01:30:57.442 --> 01:30:59.521
to put in that plot space they're making.

01:31:00.521 --> 01:31:02.041
So over here,

01:31:02.041 --> 01:31:04.962
this is a list of the standard output functions

01:31:04.962 --> 01:31:06.921
that come with Shiny.

01:31:06.921 --> 01:31:08.962
You can learn all of this on the Shiny website

01:31:08.962 --> 01:31:10.962
if you wanna look any of these up later.

01:31:12.281 --> 01:31:15.401
And they all have the same syntax again,

01:31:15.401 --> 01:31:17.682
some sort of output name,

01:31:17.682 --> 01:31:20.202
the name of the object to place in that position.

01:31:20.202 --> 01:31:21.722
And then some of them take extra arguments

01:31:21.722 --> 01:31:23.121
based on what they're doing.

01:31:24.921 --> 01:31:27.521
Right, so here are output functions.

01:31:27.521 --> 01:31:28.881
We have three of them.

01:31:28.881 --> 01:31:30.881
They're all outside of the sidebar.

01:31:30.881 --> 01:31:32.801
And you can see there's some layout functions

01:31:32.801 --> 01:31:34.442
that AI has put in here.

01:31:34.442 --> 01:31:36.202
I'm not gonna go into that.

01:31:36.202 --> 01:31:38.401
AI can do that better than a human can.

01:31:38.401 --> 01:31:40.682
It's very tedious, but straightforward.

01:31:40.682 --> 01:31:42.962
And you can learn about it on the Shiny website.

01:31:44.641 --> 01:31:45.482
Now look,

01:31:45.482 --> 01:31:47.161
each of the outputs is gonna play something

01:31:47.161 --> 01:31:48.161
with a different name.

01:31:48.161 --> 01:31:50.722
AI has unimaginatively named these things

01:31:50.761 --> 01:31:52.722
map, plot, and table.

01:31:52.722 --> 01:31:53.562
That's good.

01:31:53.562 --> 01:31:56.161
That'll let us see exactly what it's talking about.

01:31:56.161 --> 01:32:00.202
Now let's look at how map, plot, and table get built

01:32:00.202 --> 01:32:01.602
because on the server side,

01:32:01.602 --> 01:32:02.761
we're gonna build these things.

01:32:02.761 --> 01:32:04.202
So here on the UI side,

01:32:04.202 --> 01:32:06.082
there's something for leaflet output

01:32:06.082 --> 01:32:09.482
and plot output and DP output to put into the app.

01:32:10.482 --> 01:32:12.602
All right, the server instructions.

01:32:12.602 --> 01:32:14.722
This is what these look like on the app.

01:32:16.362 --> 01:32:17.521
On the server side,

01:32:17.521 --> 01:32:20.362
we're building up a list called output.

01:32:21.041 --> 01:32:21.881
And each of the elements of that list

01:32:21.881 --> 01:32:25.001
will correspond to something that we're placing into the UI.

01:32:25.001 --> 01:32:27.482
The UI is gonna look for this output list

01:32:27.482 --> 01:32:30.602
and those elements to build out the app.

01:32:30.602 --> 01:32:32.562
What we're putting into those elements

01:32:32.562 --> 01:32:35.242
won't be objects per se,

01:32:35.242 --> 01:32:37.161
like you do with regular R code.

01:32:37.161 --> 01:32:39.722
There'll be recipes of code that gets stored there

01:32:39.722 --> 01:32:42.761
for the Shiny server to pull up and run

01:32:42.761 --> 01:32:44.842
when it needs to run them.

01:32:44.842 --> 01:32:47.801
And if I asked you to guess

01:32:47.801 --> 01:32:49.962
which of these elements here would store the code

01:32:50.562 --> 01:32:52.801
that makes the output object named map,

01:32:52.801 --> 01:32:55.161
you could probably make that guess.

01:32:55.161 --> 01:32:57.161
It will be the output map one.

01:32:57.161 --> 01:32:59.082
The one that stores the code that makes plot

01:32:59.082 --> 01:33:01.362
will be output plot and so on.

01:33:01.362 --> 01:33:03.482
So the names that we choose up front

01:33:03.482 --> 01:33:04.842
we're gonna use throughout the app.

01:33:04.842 --> 01:33:07.722
They're gonna be what connects everything together.

01:33:07.722 --> 01:33:10.962
Now, how we package those code recipes up

01:33:10.962 --> 01:33:12.521
involves one other set of functions.

01:33:12.521 --> 01:33:14.442
They're called render functions.

01:33:15.921 --> 01:33:17.801
We write whatever code we want,

01:33:17.801 --> 01:33:19.521
but we wrap it in the render function

01:33:20.082 --> 01:33:21.722
and save that into the list.

01:33:21.722 --> 01:33:23.001
And the render function we use

01:33:23.001 --> 01:33:25.281
will depend on the type of thing we're saving.

01:33:27.041 --> 01:33:28.881
And we actually already saw the render functions.

01:33:28.881 --> 01:33:29.921
They were on the side, we didn't see them,

01:33:29.921 --> 01:33:31.281
but there's a render function

01:33:31.281 --> 01:33:32.962
that pairs with every output function.

01:33:32.962 --> 01:33:34.641
So if you're gonna place a table,

01:33:34.641 --> 01:33:36.602
you're gonna render a table first.

01:33:36.602 --> 01:33:38.482
If you're gonna place a plot,

01:33:38.482 --> 01:33:39.442
you're gonna render a plot.

01:33:39.442 --> 01:33:40.442
And then you have weird ones

01:33:40.442 --> 01:33:41.842
where the names don't match up,

01:33:41.842 --> 01:33:44.362
like render print and verbatim text.

01:33:44.362 --> 01:33:45.682
I can't tell you what that's about,

01:33:45.682 --> 01:33:47.801
but those things go together.

01:33:50.242 --> 01:33:51.682
All right, so this is what our code looks like.

01:33:51.682 --> 01:33:54.242
We have these render functions.

01:33:54.242 --> 01:33:55.881
They're stored into the output map

01:33:55.881 --> 01:33:57.881
and inside those render functions,

01:33:57.881 --> 01:33:59.722
it's just the familiar code we've been using all along

01:33:59.722 --> 01:34:01.842
that makes these things.

01:34:01.842 --> 01:34:04.161
But notice the dataset they're all calling

01:34:04.161 --> 01:34:06.041
or using is filtered.

01:34:06.041 --> 01:34:07.082
And filtered is something

01:34:07.082 --> 01:34:09.242
that we're also making on the server side.

01:34:11.322 --> 01:34:13.482
If you think about what filtered might be

01:34:13.482 --> 01:34:15.682
or how that app works,

01:34:15.682 --> 01:34:18.641
you might strike upon it pretty quickly.

01:34:18.682 --> 01:34:21.482
We're using the dropdown menu to filter the dataset.

01:34:21.482 --> 01:34:23.001
And then we have three separate things

01:34:23.001 --> 01:34:25.161
that work with that filtered dataset.

01:34:25.161 --> 01:34:28.281
So it's a good idea to just make the filtered dataset

01:34:28.281 --> 01:34:31.482
and have those three things borrow it.

01:34:31.482 --> 01:34:33.521
But that filtered dataset,

01:34:33.521 --> 01:34:35.761
bare and of itself doesn't appear in the UI.

01:34:35.761 --> 01:34:37.602
It's just something that floats around on the server side

01:34:37.602 --> 01:34:40.881
so we can make the three things that do appear in the UI.

01:34:40.881 --> 01:34:42.722
And that's what filtered is here.

01:34:42.722 --> 01:34:45.641
It's an intermediate object that we're making

01:34:45.641 --> 01:34:48.082
for the things downstream to use.

01:34:48.082 --> 01:34:50.801
And this object uses that input value.

01:34:50.801 --> 01:34:52.242
So here's where I'm looking up

01:34:52.242 --> 01:34:54.001
the value of the dropdown menu.

01:34:54.001 --> 01:34:55.442
And then the things downstream

01:34:55.442 --> 01:34:58.001
are gonna call this object like a function.

01:34:58.001 --> 01:34:59.682
That's just how Shiny works.

01:35:01.362 --> 01:35:03.921
But when they call it as a function,

01:35:03.921 --> 01:35:06.281
they're gonna end up running the code that's in it,

01:35:06.281 --> 01:35:08.562
which is gonna call input site.

01:35:08.562 --> 01:35:11.242
And it's gonna look up the current value of input site.

01:35:11.242 --> 01:35:14.322
And then that will be used to build the new value of map.

01:35:14.322 --> 01:35:16.521
And that's how everything always stays up to date.

01:35:16.521 --> 01:35:17.442
When it gets rerun,

01:35:17.442 --> 01:35:20.242
it's scooping up the current value that the user supply.

01:35:21.562 --> 01:35:24.801
The magic here with Shiny is,

01:35:24.801 --> 01:35:28.082
as long as the code that you use to make map,

01:35:28.082 --> 01:35:33.001
plot and table depends upon one of the input values,

01:35:33.001 --> 01:35:36.242
either directly or through a reactive intermediary,

01:35:36.242 --> 01:35:39.842
Shiny will notice that and keep track of it.

01:35:39.842 --> 01:35:41.722
And then it will take care of all the rest.

01:35:41.722 --> 01:35:43.682
It will make sure it rebuilds the things

01:35:43.682 --> 01:35:47.001
that depend on an input when that input changes.

01:35:47.001 --> 01:35:49.562
And if something does not depend on the input that changed,

01:35:49.562 --> 01:35:51.881
it won't bother rebuilding it, it's very lazy.

01:35:51.881 --> 01:35:53.482
But every time the user makes a change,

01:35:53.482 --> 01:35:55.641
everything that depends on it will be updated.

01:35:55.641 --> 01:35:56.921
And the user will be quite happy

01:35:56.921 --> 01:35:59.602
with this fast, nimble, reactive experience.

01:35:59.602 --> 01:36:03.442
And that is how you build an interactive website

01:36:03.442 --> 01:36:06.362
with only our code, in our case,

01:36:06.362 --> 01:36:08.881
and like half an hour max.

01:36:10.242 --> 01:36:13.041
Imagine doing that 10 years ago, it'd be crazy.

01:36:13.401 --> 01:36:17.041
So we now have this Shiny app, it's interactive.

01:36:17.041 --> 01:36:20.482
What we wanna do now is the masterclass

01:36:20.482 --> 01:36:23.001
of adding an AI chatbot to it.

01:36:23.001 --> 01:36:25.801
And it's going to be easier than you think.

01:36:25.801 --> 01:36:27.082
It's certainly much easier

01:36:27.082 --> 01:36:29.281
than learning to build a Shiny app would be.

01:36:31.161 --> 01:36:34.001
So we have an app, it has a dropdown menu.

01:36:34.001 --> 01:36:36.082
Our goal is to take the dropdown menu

01:36:36.082 --> 01:36:38.161
and replace it with a chatbot.

01:36:38.161 --> 01:36:39.722
The chatbot can do the filtering better

01:36:39.722 --> 01:36:41.362
than the dropdown menu and the rest of the app

01:36:41.362 --> 01:36:42.962
can respond to that.

01:36:44.362 --> 01:36:46.082
The package that makes this easy,

01:36:46.082 --> 01:36:49.281
that lets this happen, is called Query Chat.

01:36:49.281 --> 01:36:52.602
It's an R package, it also exists as a Python package.

01:36:52.602 --> 01:36:54.641
It's designed to work with Shiny

01:36:54.641 --> 01:36:57.281
to make these chatbot-powered apps.

01:37:00.722 --> 01:37:02.362
Like everything else that Posit makes,

01:37:02.362 --> 01:37:05.442
it has its own documentation page.

01:37:05.442 --> 01:37:06.921
And everything we're gonna do here

01:37:06.921 --> 01:37:08.682
is actually written up as articles

01:37:08.682 --> 01:37:10.562
on this documentation page.

01:37:10.562 --> 01:37:13.121
So it is a great resource to go back to.

01:37:14.482 --> 01:37:17.082
And I will put these links at the end of the talk

01:37:17.082 --> 01:37:18.842
so you could take a picture or screenshot of them.

01:37:18.842 --> 01:37:21.121
You don't have to worry about them right now.

01:37:22.322 --> 01:37:24.082
Here's how Query Chat works.

01:37:24.082 --> 01:37:26.562
I think it's pretty nice.

01:37:26.562 --> 01:37:29.962
It's going to talk to an LLM, like Anthropic today

01:37:29.962 --> 01:37:32.161
or some other LLM some other day.

01:37:32.161 --> 01:37:34.722
And it's going to tell that LLM

01:37:34.722 --> 01:37:38.322
that it wants it to just write SQL queries.

01:37:38.322 --> 01:37:41.082
It'll give the LLM everything your user asks for,

01:37:41.082 --> 01:37:42.962
but it will also instruct the LLM

01:37:42.962 --> 01:37:47.641
to just write SQL queries that answers the user's questions.

01:37:47.641 --> 01:37:50.202
So it doesn't give the LLM your data set.

01:37:50.202 --> 01:37:52.842
It takes your data set and it puts it

01:37:52.842 --> 01:37:54.761
into an on-disk database,

01:37:54.761 --> 01:37:57.921
either made with DuckDB or RSQLite.

01:37:57.921 --> 01:38:00.401
And so there's a database that's now sitting

01:38:00.401 --> 01:38:02.041
right next to your Shiny app.

01:38:02.041 --> 01:38:04.562
When the LLM writes a SQL query,

01:38:04.562 --> 01:38:07.082
Query Chat will give that SQL query to the database,

01:38:07.121 --> 01:38:09.041
which will then run it on the table.

01:38:09.041 --> 01:38:11.562
The database is going to be just great at running SQL.

01:38:11.562 --> 01:38:13.202
And the LLM is actually going to be pretty terrific

01:38:13.202 --> 01:38:15.121
at writing SQL because that's one of the tasks

01:38:15.121 --> 01:38:17.641
that LLM's large language models

01:38:17.641 --> 01:38:18.722
have been the most trained on,

01:38:18.722 --> 01:38:20.521
so they're quite good at it.

01:38:20.521 --> 01:38:21.842
Database runs that query.

01:38:21.842 --> 01:38:24.362
If it doesn't work, it tells the LLM to try again.

01:38:25.281 --> 01:38:28.641
When it does work, it returns the filtered data set,

01:38:28.641 --> 01:38:31.121
the data set filtered by that SQL query.

01:38:31.121 --> 01:38:34.242
And then everything downstream can use that filtered data

01:38:34.242 --> 01:38:36.962
to do their job of showing a map or a table or whatnot.

01:38:36.962 --> 01:38:40.281
And this is how you let the LLM drive your app

01:38:40.281 --> 01:38:42.801
without sending your data back to the LLM

01:38:42.801 --> 01:38:44.962
because that would consume a lot of tokens.

01:38:46.202 --> 01:38:49.281
This architecture has some real benefits.

01:38:49.281 --> 01:38:51.242
One, it's quite reliable.

01:38:51.242 --> 01:38:52.641
The database is running SQL.

01:38:52.641 --> 01:38:54.001
The LLM's writing SQL.

01:38:54.001 --> 01:38:56.202
If anything hallucinates, it just tries again

01:38:56.202 --> 01:38:57.921
before it messes anything up.

01:38:59.242 --> 01:39:00.082
It works pretty well.

01:39:00.082 --> 01:39:02.082
I mean, it's well-tested at this point.

01:39:02.082 --> 01:39:04.801
Two, it's safe for a number of reasons.

01:39:04.801 --> 01:39:08.482
One, QueryChat won't let the LLM run

01:39:08.482 --> 01:39:11.761
or it won't let the database run destructive queries.

01:39:11.761 --> 01:39:14.362
But even if it did, that database was spun up

01:39:14.362 --> 01:39:17.121
at the time the Shiny app was launched.

01:39:17.121 --> 01:39:19.041
The next time someone launches the Shiny app,

01:39:19.041 --> 01:39:20.161
a new database will be spun up.

01:39:20.161 --> 01:39:23.682
Like, there's nothing permanent that could be destroyed here.

01:39:23.682 --> 01:39:25.401
Third, it's reproducible.

01:39:25.401 --> 01:39:28.562
You can give, your user will have access to that SQL code.

01:39:28.562 --> 01:39:31.082
You can even feature it inside your Shiny app.

01:39:31.082 --> 01:39:32.041
So if they wanted to,

01:39:32.041 --> 01:39:36.161
they could then collect it and rerun it, use it later.

01:39:36.161 --> 01:39:38.842
And then four, it's kind of private

01:39:38.842 --> 01:39:42.082
in that the LLM doesn't ever really see the raw data,

01:39:42.082 --> 01:39:44.121
but it can query the data

01:39:44.121 --> 01:39:47.041
to give the user responses in the chat.

01:39:47.041 --> 01:39:49.442
And that can certainly reveal things about the data.

01:39:49.442 --> 01:39:52.362
So it's definitely not, like, secure in and of itself.

01:39:52.362 --> 01:39:55.801
This is a situation, a lot like Positive Assistant itself,

01:39:55.801 --> 01:40:00.121
where you would want to trust the model that you are using.

01:40:00.121 --> 01:40:02.442
And what we've discovered working with clients,

01:40:02.442 --> 01:40:04.401
working with AI for about a year now,

01:40:04.401 --> 01:40:06.962
is there's no way around trusting the model.

01:40:06.962 --> 01:40:09.962
If you don't trust your model, don't use it with your data.

01:40:09.962 --> 01:40:12.801
And it is very easy these days

01:40:12.801 --> 01:40:17.442
to secure a use of a model that you can trust.

01:40:17.442 --> 01:40:20.001
The model providers want to make the models trustworthy

01:40:20.001 --> 01:40:20.842
and secure, because they know

01:40:20.842 --> 01:40:22.121
no one would use them otherwise.

01:40:22.121 --> 01:40:26.041
So normally people just arrange with Anthropic, whatever,

01:40:26.041 --> 01:40:29.242
to have their data not be used.

